<exercises xml:id="quick-practice-concavity" class="unnumbered">
<title>Quick practice</title>

<exercise><statement> <p> Is <m>f(x) = 2x^{2}-7x+2</m> concave up or
concave down at
<m>x = 2</m>?</p></statement>
<solution><p> The function <m>f(x) = 2x^{2}-7x+2</m> has derivatives
<m>f'(x) = 4x-7</m> and <m>f''(x) = 4</m>. Notice that <m>f''(x)
&gt;0</m> so <m>f(x)</m> is concave up everywhere, including at <m>x =
2</m>?</p>
</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><statement> <p> Does <m>f(x) = 2x^{2}-7x+3</m> have a local
minimum or
maximum at its critical point?</p> </statement>
<solution><p> The critical point of <m>f(x) = 2x^{2}-7x+3</m> is <m>x =
\dfrac{7}{4}</m> and the second derivative of <m>f(x)</m> is <m>f''(x) =
4</m>. Since <m>f\left(\dfrac{7}{4}\right)=4&gt;0</m> (as we just saw in
the previous Question), <m>f(x)</m> is concave up at the critical point
which means the point <m>\left(\dfrac{7}{4}, -\dfrac{33}{8}\right)</m>
is a local minimum.</p>
</solution>
</exercise>

